autolisp-spec: the page on funciton getstring doesn't explain the meaning of the cr parameter (its possible values and effects).

clautolisp: doesn't implement getstring (it just returns nil).

Your mission, if you accept it, is to go fetch autocad and bricscad reference, find what values can the cr parameter take and to what effect, and update the autolisp-spec, and implement it in clautolisp.

Resolution (clautolisp 1.4.12)
------------------------------

Researched the AutoCAD 2026 and BricsCAD V22 getstring references. The
`cr` flag (the "carriage return" flag) is boolean-style — only its
nil / non-nil nature matters:

  - omitted or nil : a blank terminates the input just like Enter, so
    the returned string cannot contain spaces. "Gary Indiana Jones"
    yields "Gary".
  - any non-nil value (conventionally T): blanks are kept and only
    Enter terminates. "Gary Indiana Jones" yields "Gary Indiana Jones".

The function returns the entered string, or nil if the user just
presses Enter. AutoCAD caps the response at 132 characters; BricsCAD
documents no fixed limit.

  References:
  - AutoCAD 2026 AutoLISP Reference, getstring
    (GUID-B139EFBD-74B7-4276-B422-D2186F7D8D0A)
  - BricsCAD V22 Developer Reference, getstring
    https://developer.bricsys.com/bricscad/help/en_US/V22/DevRef/source/getstring.htm

Changes:
  - autolisp-spec: the GETSTRING entry now spells out the possible
    values of `cr` and their exact effects, and cites both vendors.
  - clautolisp: builtin-getstring was already reaching the host but
    ignored `cr` (the whole line came back regardless). It now parses
    the four calling conventions, passes the read-spaces flag to the
    host via :controls, and — for line-oriented hosts such as the
    MockHost — terminates the result at the first blank when `cr` is
    nil. A live host that already stopped at the blank sees a no-op.
  - Tests: builtin-level cr-flag tests added in autolisp-builtins-core
    (getstring-*-terminates-at-first-blank / cr-flag-keeps-blanks).

The original report's "just returns nil" no longer applies: the default
mock-host reads the line; the remaining gap was the ignored `cr` flag,
now honored.
